04846nam a22010215i 9780814748640DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147486407 a10.18574/nyu/9780814748640.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547642  a(OCoLC)76838879  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a352.23509731 aKrent, Harold J, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPresidential Powers /cHarold J Krent. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The President’s Power to Execute the Laws Passed by Congress -- t2. The Executive’s Power over Foreign Affairs -- t3. The Protective Power of the President -- t4. Presidential Immunities and Privileges -- t5. The Pardon Power -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author and Acknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFramed in Article II of the Constitution, presidential powers are dictated today by judicial as well as historical precedent. To understand the ways the president wields power as well as how this power is kept in check by other branches of government, Harold J. Krent presents three overlapping determinants of the president's role under the Constitution-the need for presidential initiative in administering the law and providing foreign policy leadership, the importance of maintaining congressional control over policymaking, and the imperative to ensure that the president be accountable to the public.Krent’s examination is sweeping, ranging from the president's ability to appoint and remove executive branch officials, to the president's role in proposing and implementing treaties and the power to conduct war, to the extent the president can refuse to turn over information in response to congressional and judicial requests. Finally, Krent addresses the history and purposes of presidential pardons.By drawing on historic and contemporary presidential actions to illustrate his points, Krent reminds us that the president is both an exalted leader with the regalia of power and an American who is and should be accountable to fellow citizens-important considerations as we elect and assess our presidents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aKrent.  aaccountable.  aactions.  aassess.  aboth.  acitizens-important.  aconsiderations.  acontemporary.  adrawing.  aelect.  aexalted.  afellow.  ahistoric.  aillustrate.  aleader.  apoints.  apower.  apresident.  apresidential.  apresidents.  aregalia.  areminds.  ashould.  athat.  awith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474782740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814748640.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814748640423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814748640/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK